    slug: "beyond-mere-christianity",
    description: `Beyond Mere Christianity is a thought-provoking Islamic book that engages directly with the theological arguments presented in C.S. Lewis's widely read apologetic work "Mere Christianity." Rather than dismissing Lewis's ideas or engaging in polemics, the author takes a scholarly and respectful approach, examining the core claims of Christian theology as presented by one of its most eloquent modern defenders and responding with arguments grounded in the Quran, authentic hadith, and rigorous logical reasoning. The book is designed for readers who have encountered Christian missionary arguments, whether through personal interactions, literature, or media, and who want a substantive Islamic response that addresses the actual substance of those arguments rather than setting up straw-man positions to knock down.

The book systematically goes through the major themes raised in Lewis's work, including the moral argument for God's existence, the concept of the trinity, the nature of Jesus, the doctrine of atonement and original sin, and the claim that Christianity represents the final and most complete revelation of divine truth. For each of these topics, the author presents the Islamic perspective clearly and comprehensively, drawing on classical Islamic scholarship as well as contemporary academic research. The discussion of the trinity, for instance, examines the historical development of this doctrine through the early church councils and contrasts it with the Quranic emphasis on strict monotheism (tawheed). The chapter on Jesus addresses the Islamic view of his prophethood, his miraculous birth, his mission to the Children of Israel, and the Quranic denial of his crucifixion and divinity — all supported with textual evidence and rational argumentation.

Written in clear, scholarly English, Beyond Mere Christianity serves multiple audiences effectively. Muslims who engage in interfaith dialogue or dawah work will find it an invaluable resource for understanding and responding to one of the most influential Christian apologetic works of the twentieth century. Muslim students studying in Western universities, where Lewis's arguments are frequently assigned reading, will benefit from having a systematic Islamic response at their fingertips. The book is also appropriate for open-minded Christians and seekers of truth who are willing to examine their beliefs critically and consider the Islamic perspective on the same theological questions. The author's tone throughout is respectful and intellectually honest, acknowledging areas of agreement between Islam and Christianity while clearly delineating the fundamental differences that separate the two faiths. This balanced approach makes the book a credible and persuasive contribution to the field of comparative theology and Islamic apologetics.`,
    metaDescription: "Beyond Mere Christianity offers a scholarly Islamic response to C.S. Lewis's apologetics. Examines trinity, atonement, and Jesus through Quran and logic."
