    slug: "brass-jaali-rehal-7-inch",
    description: `This Brass Jaali Rehal in the 7-inch size is a folding wooden Quran stand distinguished by its decorative brass jaali (lattice or perforated) panels that cover the surface of each side. The term "jaali" refers to the intricate openwork pattern carved or cast into the brass, creating a visually striking geometric or floral design that is characteristic of traditional Islamic architectural and decorative arts. In this rehal, the brass jaali panels serve a dual purpose: they transform the stand into an ornamental display piece that enhances the aesthetic of any room, and they reduce the overall weight of the stand compared to solid wooden panels while maintaining structural integrity.

The 7-inch folded size makes this rehal highly portable, easy to store, and convenient for carrying to Quran classes, mosque study circles, or when traveling. When unfolded, the stand opens to reveal the brass jaali patterns on both the front and back panels, creating an elegant frame around the open Quran resting on its surface. The lattice design allows air circulation around the book, which can help prevent moisture buildup in humid environments, and also makes the rehal lighter to carry than an equivalent all-wood model. The folding mechanism is sturdy, with metal hinges connecting the two jaali-clad panels at the center, allowing smooth opening and closing without pinching fingers or catching the pages of the Quran.

The brass jaali work on this rehal reflects the rich tradition of Islamic metalwork and geometric pattern design. The perforated patterns are typically inspired by motifs found in mosque architecture, Mughal-era craftsmanship, and classical Islamic art — including interlocking stars, arabesques, and floral vines that carry symbolic meanings related to the infinite nature of creation and the order underlying apparent complexity. This makes the rehal not just a functional reading aid but also a piece of Islamic decorative art that adds character and spiritual significance to the space where it is placed. The brass develops a natural patina over time that many users find attractive, though it can also be polished to maintain its original shine. This rehal is commonly placed on prayer mats, desks, bookshelves, and side tables, and it makes a thoughtful gift for Quran students, huffaz, teachers, elders, and anyone who appreciates the combination of traditional Islamic artistry with practical everyday utility.`,
